      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὀργή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " produces regeneration could occur to no one.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[93] Contrary to the Biblical use of language, Oecumenius explains the expression ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δικαιοσύνη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as equivalent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἕξις ἑν ψυχῇ κατʼ ἀξίαν ἐκάστῳ ἀκονεμητική",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Pott wholly arbitrarily refers the verse to the teachers of the Christian religion, paraphrasing it: iratus nequit docere religionem christianum prout fas est Deoque probatur.—Several commentators (also Kern) to this verse cite ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
